# Devils all the way down
## Start at the Bottom<!-- {"fold":true} -->

Sometimes, to tell a story properly you have to start at the extreme.  Start with the high or the low.  I start here with the bottom.  The worst of the story – perhaps even what should be considered the anti-climax.  The promise I make is that by the end of the story, you will be able to see an evolution from dismal to splendid.  Or at least to livable.

This story begins in a garage in Austin, Texas.  I’m sizing and testing some rope.  I had conveniently created a lift for our 9 ft christmas tree which must have been made of lead.  I made the lift out of 4 stout pulleys and nylon rope.  The bag the tree was in was supported by two circular loops of heavy weight rope connected by carabiners.  The heavy rope was fashioned into a loop for some other purpose (I purchased them this way), but they surrounded that bag of Christmas cheer.  The whole apparatus was driven by a ratched winch.

Like I was a condemed prisoner, my intent was to hang from this rope by the neck until dead.  I had no notion of entering Valhalla, nor was I being prodeded by demons.  I was not me at the time, but I wasn’t anyone else either.  Nonetheless, I wasn’t sure the rope would hold me.  Being an engineer, I was preparing to test it out.  I put the two ropes around my neck and began to use the crank to pull me up.  Yes, it would hold me.  

Transitioning from hypothetical to concrete is not without its moments of ponder.   Do or not to do.  Turns out this was not without its nuance.  Sure, 100% something is bringing me here.  On the other hand, I so love my family.  Would I do this to them?  Hmmm… I wonder into the kitchen where Kim is cleaning up and prop agaist a counter.   My psyche is stiffened from forehead to toes as if being wringed from a reposessing mop handle.  My body is relaxed and slouching into nothing and seemed nonchelant.  “Kim,” I say, “I think I’m going to kill myself.”

## 2 Weeks Prior<!-- {"fold":true} -->

Preceding that particular moment was a solid array of previous experiments.  It turns out that suicide is a long and arduous process.  <insert process descrition>. I had done a lot of thinking through the years of how best to end my life.  I just knew I didn’t belong here.  This life, this family and the latter I was hurting.  

At one point, I experimented with a razor blade.  Previously, I experimented with suffocation.  All just experimenting and planning and strategizing.  I wasn’t yet at the point of using them.  I wanted merely to understand what it would be like.  

The answer to all my queries was not stunning…  Dying fucking hurts.  These experiments proved it.  There was no easy way out.  Pills would work, but emetophobia had taken hold in my youth stangling percetanges of options.  EWWWW… that would be aweful. I was ironically incapacitated by fear for *any* options.  

Incidentally, I had the sad opportunity recently to spend some time with my mother just hours before she passed away.  I was stunned how painful the process of your body shutting down is.  They gave her morphine frequently through a dropper, because the kids – my brother, sister and I – would see my mom’s pale face crinkle into a scowl of pain.  Her bluing hands clasp in a permanent grip on her favorite stuffed bear.  It startled me to see my mother this way, but my brother, Jay, told me my father had a similar experience the year before, which I missed.  In his opinion, my parents were treated worse than animals.  

There’s no mercy in this dieing process.

I had laid a heavy load on my unsuspecting wife.  From here where can one go?  I’d been suffering for decades.  The consistent thoughts of self hatred and doubt was so deep I didn’t really even notice that it was literally taking my life.  I had somehow opened a box that could not be closed by me alone.

Recovering from this event and the deep long congealing anxiety, panic and depression will likely take the rest of my life.  Run away from anyone who thinks they have a story.  Like a recovering alcoholic, I would route back to those feelings of depression and the messages of shame, worthlessness, and hatred.  Depression was a normal comfortably place for me.  Even after treatment and therapy I would quickly return to that familiar feeling.  Everything else was foreign and scary.  

During my recovery I started to try and understand how I got here.  Nothing quite made sense to me.  I was a reasonably successful software engineer and engineering manager.  I hadn’t been unemployed for almost 30 years; never laid off; never fired.  

I think I know now how this lifelong journey unfolded.  I know that this story is a guess, but it’s one in which I feel confident and I feel it may be useful or enlightening in some way.  I submit it to you with the hope that it can help someone; that we can stop this from happening to our kids.   Keeping this story inside me is certainly comfortable.  I don’t want to be a bother, or worse, a continuing freak.  I'm like Pinocchio without the nose – I just want to be a real boy; I promise to stop lying to myself at least.  

I’ll bet there are many others that feel this same discomfort and discontent.  This is not a cathartic moment for me, but rather a lifelong journey starting in 1968.

## Devils on Parade

### Rusty Dusty Memories

Salem, Oregon in 1968 was a forgotten city in a forgotten state.  Fogotten by design, of course.

Oregon itself, tried hard to be a forgotten place, starting in the1960s.  Then, a local prolific writer named Stuart Holbrook created the “James G. Blain Society” focused entirely on keeping Oregon’s population growth to a minimum.   Why James G. In the words of Ralph Friedman, the second leader of the society:

***“Oregon is a lovely place to visit, but it is a mess to live in.***
…
**Oregon is a great place to visit, but no place to call home.”***

Governor McCall solidified the sentiment in the early 1970s by underlining Oregon’s diabolical situation in broad lettered billboards:  People in Oregon don’t tan, they rust…, It’s a place where ferns grow from tree bark and homes are covered in moss.

### A Moment of Infamy<!-- {"fold":true} -->
I was at a local 4th of July holiday parade.  A tradition in Salem in the 1960’s.  I was 4 years old in 1968.  Just a month or so later I would be a big 5 and I looked forward to it.  It was at that parade that my story began.  

I truly can see it and experience it now.  Somehow the events burned a deep path.  Can you imagine remembering when you were 4 years old?

I was standing next to my brother, Jay, and he was standing next to my sister Yvonne.  We must have looked amusing with our rising heights.  Suddenly I was surprised by a very loud siren.  Turning the corner was a beast I had never seen before –  A giant (to my perspective) red fire engine.  The driver was cranking an old fashioned manual siren as hard as he could.  Sending my hands to my ears.  The fire engine was also a tradition.  It belonged to the Devil’s Lake Voluntary Fire Department.  They loved participating in events like this because they could dress up like devils, scare kids and then give them candy.  I guess the candy was a crude reward for having the fortitude to take on a truckload of devils.![](data:image/jpg;base64,/9j/4AAQSkZJRgABAQAAAQABAAD/4gv4SUNDX1BST0ZJTEUAAQEAAAvoAAAAAAIA

For me, being beaten and pureed by the siren of the devils, I was wholly terrified.  My brother remembers this too, because I completely came unglued in terror.  At last I looked into the face of one of the devils.  He was about a half a block away, but to me it seems like he was 100 yards away.  I had to escape.  The devil saw my fear and, as I think about it now, likely moved toward me to provide me with my requisite calming candy to make everything better. 

When he made his move toward me my insides shattered like an unlucky mirror – I bolted.  

I must have looked something like bugs-bunny putting a rabbit shaped hole in a wall.  My parents were in a nearby store looking at carpet samples.  I’m sure that they were right behind me, but again, my experience was proportional.  I ran for what seemed like a mile straight to the comforting legs of my mother who had her back to the street.  I gripped her legs in utter trembling.![](data:image/jpg;base64,/9j/4AAQSkZJRgABAQEBLAEsAAD/4RDcRXhpZgAATU0AKgAAAAgABAE7AAIAAAAG

This is a direct recollection, the transfixed events of that day are solidly nailed to my mind with a clarity that may seem impossible.  My memory surely can provide a time altered version of history.  I have investigated my recollections for accuracy.  My mind's eye may not be perfect, but this is not fiction.

The devil ran after me into the carpet shop, where I was cowering in a terrified clinging pile.  He (while keeping character by the way) said something like “you’re going to buy some carpet huh?”  He used a gravelly voice like a devil.  He gave me a piece of candy.  Or rather I believe he gave it to my mother.

Years later, in discussing the event with my mom and my brother, my recollection was verified, but what I didn’t know is that my mother chastized that asshole grandly for chasing a little boy.  “What kind of person would do that?” she asked.

### The Messy Aftermath<!-- {"fold":true} -->
I calmed down after going to my mother, but I don’t remember anything else from that day.  What I do remember though is the messy aftermath.  I immediately began to have a similarly terrified response anytime I heard a siren.  Salem was big enough to have frequent ambulances, fire trucks, police cars, all fitted with 1960s sirens that sounded similar to the one at the parade.  Not everyday of course, but that didn’t matter to my tiny brain.  I was convinced that the devils were coming after me.  

I recall a handful of those early instances of fear.  My little mind raced away and on occasion mushroomed into an event I can recall.  For instance, at times when I heard the siren and panicked, I recall looking for my mom or I would hide somewhere in the house until the sirens went away (usually behind the formidable couch).  Fortunately they would never come again, but my little mind was solidly expectant.

One of the most impactful moments came as I was taking a bath.  I heard the sirens, I felt them getting closer and closer.  I was in the tub and exposed – I had to get to safety.  I ran out of the bathroom naked and wet, splattering the floors.  My mom was nowhere to be found.   With this and no time to spare, I double panicked.  There was nowhere to hide if they were coming to my house.  I ran outside, again completely naked, and raced around the perimeter of the house to find her.  I’m sure she was in the garage, or the side of the house.  There was a door from the kitchen to the garage.  I don’t recall much other than opening the door and the screendoor and running like hell.

This happened over and over.  Every siren – every terror – created a small wall of devils inside me.  They lined up first at my feet and then kept going.  This is the beginning of the lifetime torture I provided for myself.

## Pile up the Devils<!-- {"fold":true} -->

After that parade and the following fear, many strange physical things started to happen.  To be sure I don’t know if any of these issues are directly related to my affliction – which I will now label as PTSD.  What I do know is that some of the issues were relatively common, many though were not at all common.

The first of these was serious childhood asthma.  I say “serious” not because anyone told me it was.  In fact, it may have been totally textbook for 1968 - 1969.  For me, it was another line of devils.  I would have asthma attacks where I could barely breathe.  I can still see my mothers face through my tears, wheezing in and out each breath.  At times I would cough so hard that I would throw up.  On those occasions mother provided me with a pot from the kitchen to barf into.  

In fact, my family loved to watch Star Trek on television.  I was pretty young to watch the show, but my parents didn’t regulate too strenuously.  It was shown sort of late in the evening for me, around 8:30 or 9:00.  It was dark for sure.  The only time that I would see the show is when I was up with an asthma attack (seemed to be worse at night for some reason).  There I was on the couch, my pan in front of me crying, barfing, and a bit fearfully watching this show that frankly I should not have been watching (it was scary for 1968, 1969!).  My brother and sister were not excited about me being there, throwing up into a container and trying not to watch the show through bleary eyes.

My mom struggled to find a way to calm down the attacks.  I was barely able to breathe.  One way to combat the terrible wheezing was steam.  My mom would provide a pot of steaming water all wrapped in cloth so as not to be hot with a towel over my head to direct the steam.  At bad moments we would go to the bathroom and start up the shower as hot as possible and fill the room with steam.  I’m not sure it helped, but at least I was comforted by my mom in the process. 

After many battles with asthma, we hit one that even my stalwart mother couldn’t accept without action.  They raced me to the hospital emergency room where they immediately placed me in a plastic covered housing.  The only thing I remember was looking out of the oxygen tent to the warped faces talking outside the tent.  I’m sure my folks were talking to the emergency doctor, but had no idea what they were saying.  I got better, but it was scarey.

These events provided row after row of devils piling up.  I was not in control of my thoughts and frankly didn’t think emotions existed.  No one else would know what I experienced.  My mom did know something was wrong.  I’m sure she consoled me the best she could.  I don’t recall ever having the maturity to recognize that I could die.  Or that there was even a risk.  I just knew I was not right.

My mom now had the answer though – I had allergies that needed treatment.  My mom and I traversed the path to the Salem Clinic on Lafayette street just off Commercial over and over again regarding my lungs.  Now, I was going again, but to treat these allergies.  They tested my back for various allergens and it was determined I had a particularly strong allergy to a host of nefarious criminal ingredients – dust, grass pollen, and mold.  

Since Oregon is mostly held together by pollen, mold, and moss, keeping the allergies at bay was an uphill battle.  At the doctors recommendation, my mother scrubbed every inch of the house and put plastic covers over our bedsprings.  All of this was to the tune of confused siblings who did not think this was reasonable at all.  I felt small and broken.  I was causing all manner of unusual activity that drew unwanted attention.  Not the least of which was the incessant allergy shots.

Let’s face it, kids don’t like shots.  I was no exception.  My mom, who didn’t drive a car until the mid 80s, and I would walk down Winter street to the clinic two times a week for what seemed like my entire life.  At the end of each walk, I was greeted by the little shot, waited to make sure I didn't have a bad reaction, and then off we went walking home with my little hand in hers.  On extra stressful days, we would occasionally stop for a milkshake across the street at Whites Diner.

But again I was reminded by my siblings that this was strange and impactful for them.  My brother had to go to a neighbor's house frequently to be watched.  I’m guessing my sister did some watching too as she was about 13 I would guess.  The issue and the upheaval reminded me that something was fundamentally wrong – devils.

For some reason, baths made me feel great.  I loved the warm water and playing with our plastic boats and tow cars.  I had this really big plastic tugboat that I would use as a ferry to take my cars from place to place.  Oftentimes, during heavy created storms, the inventory would be a complete loss, all sinking to the bottom of the ocean.

During one such bath I noticed that my leg up near my “pumper” (as my dad would describe it) had a little volcano on it.  The volcano was spewing smoke out of my leg into the water.  So cool.  My mom, investigating, determined that it was not smoke but rather pus.  It was a little worrying, but my mom tried to keep it together.  We now headed to the Salem Clinic for a new problem in addition to the shots.  

My doctor reported that my 5 year old body was just having a tough time processing some type of infection.  While it’s not uncommon for lymph nodes, one of several in the groin area, to swell up.  I now understand  that most of the reasons for swelling were just awful and not likely in a young boy.  To top it off, since the swollen lymph node was spewing pus it sent a little chill into the doctor visit.  I needed to be tested for all the reasons a lymph node would swell – cancer, autoimmune diseases, sexually transmitted diseases (ya, not likely) – all of which were way over my head.  All I know is that I have to go to more doctors and more types of doctors who love nothing more poking and prodding.

This condition was super rare in a child of 5.  My parents took it seriously and moved quickly on the tests.  One of these tests, for some reason, was to see if I had tuberculosis.  The test for it was one that I clearly recall.  Two bubbles were created on each of my tiny inner arms by injecting something under the skin.  You wait for a while (jeez seemed like forever) and then some recognition would emerge mysteriously like reading tea leaves.  Not for me though, in my instance, one of the bumps was determined to be tuberculosis, but the other was negative.  This was rare.  I wish I could have responded with a fine “Fucking hell, just leave me alone!”, but my parents would not allow swearing.  

Needless to say, the rare test results pushed another round of wet and cold walks to various clinics.  Doctors were super interested in this phenomenon.  Apparently, there were analysis gaps at the time that grasped their imagination.  They decided they would write up this case in a medical journal.  After repeating the test several times (more needles) and getting the same results, they decided to do one more test and take photos for the article.

My mom seemed really uplifted by the spotlight.  She reported it to me as if I would be proud to have this malformation documented for the public to see.  Doctors would don thick reading glasses and peer magically and mysticly into my strange scrawny arms for all eternity.  Maybe find a cure! The cure, of course, was not the result of any of these tests or the article that proved I was a completely foreign antibody to the earth.  

There is something very very wrong and the devils piled up.

The result of all these tests ended up putting me in the hospital to surgically remove my still swollen and leaking lymph node.  The only image I remember from the whole event at the time was the green masked and hatted giant who wheeled me in for surgery.  Afterwards, though, I got pretty much anything I wanted while I was in the hospital.  Shoot, I thought it was a grand place.  To this day, I still have a tender scar to remind me.  

Nobody I knew had had surgery for a rare disorder.  That I was a rarity was not cool for me.  I was a freak.

As I grew up, while these events didn’t leave my consciousness, they certainly took a back seat to playing with the kids in the neighborhood.  There were a lot of devils piled up, but I could still see over the top.  At the same time, though, other behavior sprouted.  It was drilled into me that because of my asthma, there were many things I couldn’t do.  Rigorous playing (baseball, football, running) almost always ended in asthma attacks.  I got used to being cautious.  I was delicate and easily broken.![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAASAAAACiCAIAAABu7oewAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAA

We eventually were able to move out of Kumlar Street rental.  We moved to our house on Winter street.  At 6 I was having a terrible time processing that we moved away from my block.  To be sure, we only moved 6 blocks.  Not only were my parents ecstatic at being able to buy a house, but they were happy that we were right next to the high school (South Salem) and middle school (Leslie is gone now).  We would be going to the same elementary school, Mckinley up at the end of High Street.  I hadn’t quite made it to elementary school at that point.

I joke now that I had “failed” preschool.  My parents tried to take me to another preschool (The Little Red Schoolhouse) the year before.  The attempt utterly failed because I could not leave the comfort of my mom and could not seem to make any friends or even just play with the group.  The recommendation was to hold me out of school for a year and then try again.  Instead, my mom found another preschool that was closer to home and more familiar to me.  It was a program taking place in a church basement.  It worked!  I made a friend and had a fantastic time at school.  This was a great improvement.

I remember a few moments from that experience.  I used to laugh heartily when, at rest time, the teachers, hair raised high in a credible bouffant, would walk through and over the kids.  My friend Paul would move his head so he could look up their dresses.  It was hilarious, I thought.  The other incident was just an offhand question from one of the other kids.  She asked why my hands were so purple.  I looked down.  Indeed my hands were deep purple, likely from the cool room.

“You have a bit of poor circulation in your hands”, my mom would surmise.  We never really pursued it other than to ask the doctor.  There was no result.  However, my mind grasped onto that fact.  I was convinced that I was dying of some rare disease.  I know, because I may not be from earth.  This fact started when I finally started watching astronauts go to the moon.  We were well into the Apollos when I started to pick it up much later.

After my successful introduction to school I was rarin’ to go to McKinley.  McKinley, a former hospital, was a menacing building to me.  It was a long 12 block walk every day – rain or shine.  My brother was 3 grades ahead of me.  He said he would grease the skids for me.  My sister was already well into high school.  But, my friend Paul and I were in the same class.  Mrs Chamberlain and my mom lobbied hard for that so I would be more comfortable.   (We also had what we thought was the prettiest teacher of them all.)  The problem though was that there was a giant siren outside my school room.![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAfQAAAF3CAIAAADckC6rAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAA

Outside that schoolroom – playing on the monkey bars, double stepping across the hanging bars or twirling around the pull up bars.  All hyper dangerous, and way fun! At home, I was ok.  When I was in that classroom, I sat in constant terror that the fire alarm would go off.  Eventually I knew it would because there were “fire drills.” They would not divulge when these horror provoking fire drills would happen, so I had to sit and wait and worry.  The devils had got the best of me.

Not for me.  The association between the parade and this fear was broken.  I didn’t put that story together and neither did my parents.  

The fear and dread of fire alarms followed me through every grade.  Upon being assigned to a classroom, I would immediately assess if the fire alarm was too close or not.  The worst possible classroom I had was in the basement of McKinley.  I was learning to write and the fact that I was left handed made me an oddity to teach.  At least that was true of this teacher.  She tried and tried to work with me on the location of paper, the way I hold the pencil.  No matter what she tried, I curled my wrist over the top of the paper and continued to drag my hand though ink and graphite.  It was fine for me, because I wasn’t different than everyone else, except for the fact that leftyism was rare.

Eventually, the location of the fire alarms mattered less.  Into middle school and high school, I stopped looking for this location and, at least, stopped fearing fire drills.  Some of this was due to the removal of the old style fire sirens and, at least in high school, they were replaced with less triggering alarms.  Victory!  Sort of…![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAfQAAAH0CAYAAADL1t+KAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAA

While the direct association of sirens and fear faded, the fear, however, didn’t go away.  I was still inexplicably in constant fear.  There was no reason for it of course, but reasoning was not propelling me.  We will come back to this subject again a bit later.

Junior high and puberty provided the perfect backdrop for the next oddity that really did change my life.  When I was between 11 and 13, I began to experience strange sounds in my ears.  They would burst out – high shrilling screams and a low subtle rumbling.  In one instance, as I lay awake in my bed, I heard the unmistakable rumble of an idling 18 wheeler outside my window.  Strange, I thought, but I’m sure they will drive off soon.  The sound never left though and I began to wonder what was going on out there.  My bed was right next to the window, so I sat up and looked out on a quiet dark night on Winter street.  No trucks, no cars, just me.

My hands tentatively moved up to cover my ears.  There was no change in the sound.  I could plug one ear and sounds would disappear, but in my right ear the rumbling truck continued no matter what I did.  There was certainly the thought that I was going nuts in the more colloquial sense. 

I kept all the fear and anxiety unnamed and inside.   Eventually, I would ask my mother, “Am I from outer space?"  She assured me I was a solid earthling and none of the problems are my fault.  I was not convinced.

In addition to the ringing ears, I was also experiencing significant "stomach trouble.”  I felt terrible all the time, but mostly when I was in junior high.  I truly had no way to align my stomach issues with panic attacks and constant fear.  This was just normal for me.

Once again, after informing what must have been a very tired mother, I was off to more appointments.  These were different types of doctors – ear doctors and stomach specialists.  My childhood doctor (Dr Sessions) was likely getting the picture that I didn’t really have anything wrong.  But you can’t just give up.   So there I was again, this time at bigger medical facilities in the much larger mega city (at least for us Salemites) – Portland.

There, I was x-rayed, CT Scanned, gastrointestinally inspected with various dyes.  The results were simple, but weighty for me.  My stomach was not a source of problems, that was 100%.  But what was it?  My mom had to face the fact that I may need counseling.  

The problem with my hearing was a little different.  No brain tumors, no illnesses, no consistent loud noises, and no sounds actually coming out of my ears.  (He literally put a stethoscope on my ears.)  The results were not complete yet.  

I make this period feel like it was all terrible, but that’s not the case.  Remember I didn’t know of anything that would affect my being a kid (except for the asthma).  For the most part, I really tried to just ignore the issues and move on with my fun.  In fact, the more I did, the better I felt.

These formidable years were excellent to me.  I liked doing so many things.  Eventually I began to focus on music.  I was a “talented young man from Salem Oregon” eventually, but in the short term I focused on Jazz.  We had elite jazz choirs at all my schools and getting into those small groups became my fixation.  I had natural talent as a singer.  I also took up the guitar and found it easy for me to pass my little guitar classes.  I began to perform little bits of music for my family.  Sometimes at holiday gatherings.  I would listen to a song I liked and transcribe it to my guitar.  If someone wanted to hear something, I could provide it.

The key here though was not that I was some ultra-talented musician, the key was throwing myself in completely.  Immersing myself in every aspect of music.  The sound, the singing, mimicking my favorite acts (got to love Elvis), but most importantly, I realized that I could both perform and write the music.

This will be a thematic tendency.  I’m a “meta” person.  I didn’t want to read books, I wanted to write them, I didn’t just enjoy art, I wanted to create it.  Music though would be my sole focus until well into my twenties.

Meanwhile, back at the autolaryngologist, we were running out of tests and diagnosis, so according to my doctor there was just one more test.  He had me stand in the middle of the room, close my eyes and march in place.  Up and down my legs went, while I focused on not moving from that spot.  Super easy test and I was smashing it out of the park I think.  That’s until my doctor quickly stopped me.  I opened my eyes and found myself staring directly at the wall not 6 inches from my face.  I was stunned, how did I move that far?  The answer – vertigo.

Having concluded his assessment, he was ready to diagnose.  I had Menier’s Disease (or Menier’s Syndrome). This condition is not really a disease, they will tell you, it’s just a set of symptoms that emerge together with hearing loss.  I had lost some hearing in my right ear, but not enough to really affect me at the time.

He said that Menier’s is extremely rare in someone my age (I think I was 13 then).  He said that typically it would start in your 50’s and the progress more forcefully from there.  I was utterly stunned.  I mean fucking hell, another rare condition to top off the others?  I must have looked shocked and saddened at the appointment.  My mom was with me.  

The doctor asked, “what sort of things do you like to do?”  He was making a play that this wouldn’t likely be a hindrance to me even though the disease is likely to progress until I’m deaf and unable to stand or keep food down from vertigo.  

“Music,”  I replied.

I’ll bet my mom saw the blood drain from his face.  He got trapped.  He said, “well you may want to take up a different hobby.”  This was not a hobby to me.  I dedicated my life to music and expected it to be my career.  It was devastating and angering.  I didn’t know what to do with all these feelings and thoughts.

Fortunately, although I was diagnosed with this weird thing, it didn’t affect my music at all at the moment, so I kept going.  Everyone I worked with was happy I continued, particularly myself.  I did get into that elite group in middle school and got into the master choir.  In fact, the absolutely brilliant choral teacher, Mrs Branstetter, told me she had never had anyone compose a different rendition of a song.  I was hooked.

Other classes did not go so well.  For some reason I couldn’t memorize facts, I had to have my hands on things to understand them.  Topics like math and science required that sort of focus, but I didn’t see a way though at the time.  The actual reason behind my difficulty didn’t get recognized until I was college.  Nothing out of the ordinary – I was just a very slow reader.  I can read, but it takes me forever to understand.  

Geometry, believe it or not, was a tremendous downfall.  Geometry is all memorizing formulas, lemmas, proofs, acute angles and all manner of triangles and polygones.  The only word that made sense to me was “Chord.”  Unfortunately, it didn’t have anything to do with music.  I was unprepared for the amount of work that would be required.

I really failed Geometry, but in middle school, it was considered a dividing line.  There was no reason to dehumanize a child with a failure.  Instead, they determined that I was just not college material.  I was destined for the trenches.  My schedule forward would focus on the kind of math required to be a mechanic or a draftsman.  Music was still my electoral subject.

OK, time to summarize my outlook:

1 I’m a freak who is fundamentally broken.  I’m sure I will find out what was really wrong in the future.  I would die of some strange disease, or more likely a heart attack, due to the constant state of fear that made my heart pump like train.

⠀
2 I’m not very smart.  I can’t pass classes, I can’t read, I can’t keep up.  Even though my grades were sort of in the mid Bs, I still couldn’t be smart like the other kids.  People are starting to become exhausting to me.

⠀
3 “I can’t, because I’m disabled” – so many things that normal people would do – play football, basketball, tennis, I could try these things but won’t be able to continue.  I had asthma and frankly every time I turned around to shoot the basketball I would fall over.  My ears ring and I can’t be in classes.

⠀
This was my fundamental world view.

Not a day passed as I routed myself through school where I was free of panic attacks.  They started with sirens, but molded later into pure fear.  Fear of what?  I didn’t know.  During the panic attacks I felt as if I would throw up.

To understand what these panic attacks felt like, you have to envision how you may feel when you walk through a haunted house.  You tense up, knowing that a jump scare may be coming.  When jump does come, there is a point in time where your body is reacting to the fear even though your mind has not quite processed it.  It’s that feeling, sustained anywhere from 20 minutes to an hour depending on the situation.

I didn’t know what to call these attacks, so I kept it quiet.  My mom knew that I was having trouble, but as I went through high school, I worked hard to keep it to myself.  I didn’t want yet another instance of being shamed (he’s crazy) and judged (how many more doctors do I need?).

The panic occurred consistently.  Particularly if I had eaten something.  Food was not a good thing for me.  I adjusted to eating just enough to get to the penultimate moment of “full.”  I found a great strategy was to leave the last bites of all food on the plate.  Then it looked like I had eaten, but I still didn’t feel full.  If I did feel full, it was trouble.

Panic attacks continued all through high school, undergraduate college and into my first years working for the Federal Government in Washington, DC.

They were so constant, and my adaptability was improving, so while I couldn’t go to a movie or go out to dinner (god forbid) without significant pre-thought. I was able to make it through a lot of the workday.  

There was another fantastical side benefit of my panic attacks.  After the attack dragged on for 20 or 30 minutes I would experience utter peace for about 5 - 10 minutes afterward.  This peace was like nothing I had ever felt and I wanted it.  I just didn’t want to go through the process of earning it.  When the peace began, my head was clear as a bell.  My tense body relaxed and I felt like I was floating in space.  I wanted that experience to continue forever, but alas, it ended all too soon.

During therapy later in life, after exploring these attacks, It was determined that the panic was so intense that I likely dissociated.  I wished that I could bottle that feeling.  But, in the end it was not a very good solution.
